    "text": "Translating long-term memory into embodied plans is a sub-challenge of partial observability, defined by the need to convert internally stored abstract representations into actionable motor sequences, not an independent fundamental challenge.",
    "topic": "Definitional Scope"
  },
  {
    "text": "Partial observability is a necessary condition for the challenge of memory translation to arise, but memory translation is not a necessary response to partial observability, as purely reactive policies can suffice.",
    "topic": "Necessity and Sufficiency"
  },
  {
    "text": "A challenge X is independent of challenge Y iff X can occur in the absence of Y; memory translation depends on partial observability because it presupposes hidden state that memory resolves.",
    "topic": "Independence Criterion"
  },
  {
    "text": "The contradiction between A and B dissolves if A is interpreted as mapping a specific sub-problem under partial observability and B is interpreted as denying that this sub-problem constitutes a separate fundamental category.",
    "topic": "Resolution through Categorization"
  }
